<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-543  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 543.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  August 1990 v78 n8 p1317(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Formal methods for generating protocol conformance test sequences.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dahbura, Anton T.; Sabnani, Krishan K.; Uyar, M. Umit.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Formal methods are necessary for the protocol conformance testingof communications protocols because of the wide range andcomplexity of such protocols.andP;  Testing is further complicated bylimitations on the controllability and observability of protocolimplementations.andP;  Four major methods of conformance testgeneration, each based on the finite-state machine (FSM) concept,have been identified.andP;  They comprise the transition tour method,the distinguishing sequences method, the characterizing sequencesmethod, and the unique input/output sequences method, and are usedto test the control portion of the protocol specification.andP;  Fourformal test methods have been defined by various standards bodiesto take account of the controllability and observability factors.andO;They include the local testing method, the distributed testingmethod, the coordinated testing method, and the ferry testingmethod.andP;  Each method is explained and some of the issues arisingfrom them are noted.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TestingProtocolMethodsCommunications TechnologyFinite State Automata.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Local testing method. (chart)Distributed testing method. (chart)Remote testing method. (chart)Ferry testing method. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>